My constituents want a fair electoral system and a citizenship question to ensure it with accurate information. It's a basic matter of fairness and justice. I joined House colleagues to make this case to the Atty General. 

You can read our letter here:  https://bit.ly/2Sbcdmo

States like California, which must attract illegal aliens to replace those fleeing bad policies, hold an unfair advantage over states that maintain rule of law. You could easily call this foreign interference in U.S. elections.
Far from gerrymandering, which Democrats practice when they're able, a citizenship question would more fairly distribute representation and taxpayer dollars.

Sanctuary states, losing citizen population and business, depend on inflated numbers to skew Congressional representation and federal funds in their favor. 

This is clear example of gaming of our electoral system and perpetuates failing liberal economic model of gov't dependence

There's no reason why a citizen or legal immigrant shouldn't fill out a Census form with a citizenship question, which Commerce has asked many times in the past. There's a well established precedent. 

Democrats are concerned illegal aliens might not respond, however.

Happy Birthday to the United States of America, the Greatest Nation on Earth!

The rockets' red glare. The bombs bursting in air. Our National Anthem celebrates America's military history. The 4th of July celebrates our hard-won Independence. A display of U.S. military hardware in the nation's capital, as the fireworks burst, seems like a fitting tribute!
